// MORE ABOUT ENVELOPES:  Remember that the use of levelScale and timeScale arguments of EnvGen make an Env very flexible -- Env is essentially a specification of the \ul \ulc2 proportion\ulnone  of values and times that can be stretched. It's not possible to pass an Env as an argument, or as a Control, to a Synth.  Arguments of a Synth CAN however be used in an enclosed Env specification to change its shape as it runs, and you can even use Controls, as shown in last week's "Klank" code, to pass Arrays to change the levels and times Arrays of an Env inside a Synth. However, this can get messy if you want a lot of flexibility.  One simpler way of attaining a variety of  envelopes to control running Synths is to define multiple versions of that Synth, each containing a different envelope.  But if you still want more flexibility, you can define SynthDefs that do not output any sound, but that function as envelope generators by writing their control rate outputs to control busses.  The code below implements this method, and also forms an introduction to the class Bus, which provides a powerful facility for patching audio as well as control signals between running Synths.\
\
\
\
//Use this for the second part of the assignment\cf0 \
( \cf2 // same as SynthDef above, but will use Bus.control inputs to for amp and indexCtls\cf0 \
